    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-01-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-01-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="306"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d306">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.114/212</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Secretary of the Treasury</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mellon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-01-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 27, 1920</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Reference is made to your letter of the 17th
                    instant, (File S O 811.114/204:) with its enclosure of a communication from the
                    Italian Embassy<note n="96" xml:id="d306fn96">Not printed.</note> regarding the
                    practice of collectors of customs under T. D. 38218, of sealing liquors listed
                    as sea stores on vessels arriving in ports of the United States, and keeping
                    them under seal during the vessel’s stay in port.</p>
                <pb facs="0680" n="560" xml:id="pg_560"/>
                <p>You are advised that following the receipt of an opinion rendered by the Attorney
                    General in the matter,<note n="97" xml:id="d306fn97">32 Op. Att. Gen. 96.</note>
                    this Department has prepared for publication as a Treasury Decision<note n="98"
                        xml:id="d306fn98">Treasury Decision 38248.</note> at an early date, an
                    amendment to the decision mentioned above, by reason of which liquors on foreign
                    vess.els will be placed under seal while the vessels are in port and such
                    portions thereof released from seal from time to time as may be required for use
                    by the officers and crews.</p>
                <p>Appropriate instructions have been issued to collectors of customs at the various
                    ports by telegram directing a modification of their practice in accordance with
                    the foregoing.</p>
                <p>By direction of the Secretary.</p>
                <p>Respectfully,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Jouett Shouse</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Assistant Secretary</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
